The paper deals with the analysis of human activity data collected from mobile networks to gain insights into the structure of cities. This falls under the domain of social computing (cs.SI) as it involves the study of human behavior and social interactions. The paper also uses visualization techniques to present the results, which could be classified under computer graphics (cs.CY) and scientific visualization (cs.SD). The analysis of land use patterns and functional clusters could be categorized under computational engineering (cs.CE). Finally, the paper also touches upon the potential real-time applications of the approach, which could be relevant to human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
